  }, "the most common response to distress is to seek out people we like and trust to help us and give us the courage to go on. We may also calm down by engaging in a physical activity like biking or going to the gym. We start learning these ways of regulating our feelings from the first moment someone feeds us when we\u2019re hungry, covers us when we\u2019re cold, or rocks us when we\u2019re hurt or scared. But if no one has ever looked at you with loving eyes or broken out in a smile when she sees you; if no one has rushed to help you (but instead said, \u201CStop crying, or I\u2019ll give you something to cry about\u201D), then you need to discover other ways of taking care of yourself. You are likely to experiment with anything\u2014drugs, alcohol, binge eating, or cutting\u2014that offers some kind of relief.  (p. 88)", mdx("span", {
